</TABLE>

<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF"><B><I>Prompt Corrective
Regulatory Action.</I></B>&#160;The OTS is required to take
certain supervisory actions against undercapitalized institutions, the severity
of which depends upon the institution&#146;s degree of undercapitalization.&#160; Generally, a savings institution that has a
ratio of total capital to risk weighted assets of less than 8%, a ratio of Tier
1 (core) capital to risk-weighted assets of less than 4% or a ratio of core
capital to total assets of less than 4% (3% or less for institutions with the
highest examination rating) is considered to be &#147;undercapitalized.&#148;&#160; A savings institution that has a total
risk-based capital ratio less than 6%, a Tier 1 capital ratio of less than 3%
or a leverage ratio that is less than 3% is considered to be &#147;significantly
undercapitalized&#148; and a savings institution that has a tangible capital to
assets ratio equal to or less than 2% is deemed to be &#147;critically
undercapitalized.&#148;&#160; Subject to a narrow
exception, the OTS is required to appoint a receiver or conservator for an
institution that is &#147;critically undercapitalized.&#148;&#160; The regulation also provides that a capital restoration plan must
be filed with the OTS within 45 days of the date a savings institution receives
notice that it is &#147;undercapitalized,&#148; &#147;significantly undercapitalized&#148; or
&#147;critically undercapitalized.&#148;&#160;
Compliance with the plan must be guaranteed by any parent holding
company.&#160; In addition, numerous
mandatory supervisory actions become immediately applicable to an
undercapitalized institution, including, but not limited to, increased
monitoring by regulators and restrictions on growth, capital distributions and
expansion.&#160; The OTS could also take any
one of a number of discretionary supervisory actions, including the issuance of
a capital directive and the replacement of senior executive officers and
directors. </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF"><B><I>Insurance of Deposit
Accounts</I></B><I>.</I>&#160;&#160; The Bank is a member of the SAIF.&#160; The FDIC maintains a risk-based assessment
system by which institutions are assigned to one of three categories based on
their capitalization and one of three subcategories based on examination
ratings and other supervisory information.&#160;
An institution&#146;s assessment rate depends upon the categories to which it
is assigned.&#160; Assessment rates for SAIF
member institutions are determined semiannually by the FDIC and currently range
from zero basis points for the healthiest institutions to 27 basis points for
the riskiest. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">In addition to the assessment for deposit insurance, institutions are
required to make payments on bonds issued in the late 1980s by the Financing Corporation (&#147;FICO&#148;) to
recapitalize the predecessor to the SAIF. By law, there has been equal sharing
of FICO payments between SAIF and BIF members since January 1, 2000. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">26</FONT></P>

<HR SIZE=5 NOSHADE>

<P STYLE="page-break-after:always"></P>


<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">The Bank did not pay an assessment for deposit insurance in 2004,
however, its payments toward the FICO bonds amounted to approximately
$107,000.&#160; The FDIC has authority to
increase insurance assessments.&#160; A
significant increase in SAIF insurance premiums would likely have an adverse
effect on the operating expenses and results of operations of the Bank.
Management cannot predict what insurance assessment rates will be in the
future. </FONT></P>


<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">Insurance of deposits may be terminated by the FDIC upon a finding that
the institution has engaged in unsafe or unsound practices, is in an unsafe or
unsound condition to continue operations or has violated any applicable law,
regulation, rule, order or condition imposed by the FDIC or the OTS. The
management of the Bank does not know of any practice, condition or violation
that might lead to termination of deposit insurance. </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF"><B><I>Loans to One
Borrower.</I></B>&#160;
Federal law provides that savings institutions are generally subject to
the limits on loans to one borrower applicable to national banks.&#160; A savings institution may not make a loan or
extend credit to a single or related group of borrowers in excess of 15% of its
unimpaired capital and surplus.&#160; An
additional amount may be lent, equal to 10% of unimpaired capital and surplus,
if secured by specified readily-marketable collateral.&#160; At December 31, 2004, the Bank&#146;s limit on
loans to one borrower was $13.8 million and the Bank&#146;s largest aggregate
outstanding loans and extensions of credit to one borrower was $12.3 million. </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF"><B><I>QTL Test</I>.</B>&#160; The HOLA requires savings institutions to
meet a qualified thrift lender test.&#160;
Under the test, a savings association is required to either qualify as a
&#147;domestic building and loan association&#148; under the Internal Revenue Code or
maintain at least 65% of its &#147;portfolio assets&#148; (total assets less: (i)
specified liquid assets up to 20% of total assets; (ii) intangibles, including
goodwill; and (iii) the value of property used to conduct business) in certain
&#147;qualified thrift investments&#148; (primarily residential mortgages and related
investments, including certain mortgage-backed securities) in at least 9 months
out of each 12 month period.&#160; </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">A savings institution that fails the qualified thrift lender test is
subject to certain operating restrictions and may be required to convert to a
bank charter.&#160; As of December 31, 2004,
the Bank maintained 74% of its portfolio assets in qualified thrift investments
and, therefore, met the qualified thrift lender test. Recent legislation has
expanded the extent to which education loans, credit card loans and small
business loans may be considered &#147;qualified thrift investments.&#148; </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF"><B><I>Limitation on
Capital Distributions</I></B><I>.</I>&#160; OTS regulations
impose limitations upon all capital distributions by a savings institution,
including cash dividends, payments to repurchase its shares and payments to
shareholders of another institution in a cash-out merger. Under current
regulations, an application to and the prior approval of the OTS is required
prior to any capital distribution if the institution does not meet the criteria
for &#147;expedited treatment&#148; of applications under OTS regulations (<I>i.e.</I>, generally, examination ratings in
the two top categories), the total capital distributions for the calendar year
exceed net income for that year plus the amount of retained net income for the
preceding two years, the institution would be undercapitalized following the
distribution or the distribution would otherwise be contrary to a statute, regulation
or agreement with OTS.&#160; If an
application is not required, the institution must still provide prior notice to
OTS of the capital distribution if, like the Bank, it is a subsidiary of a
holding company.&#160; In the event the
Bank&#146;s capital fell below its regulatory requirements or the OTS notified it
that it was in need of more than normal supervision, the Bank&#146;s ability to make
capital distributions could be restricted.&#160;
In addition, the OTS could prohibit a proposed capital distribution by
any institution, which would otherwise be permitted by the regulation, if the OTS determines that
such distribution would constitute an unsafe or unsound practice. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">27</FONT></P>
<HR SIZE=5 NOSHADE>

<P STYLE="page-break-after:always"></P>


<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF"><B><I>Assessments</I></B><I>.</I>&#160;
Savings institutions are required to pay assessments to the OTS to fund
the agency&#146;s operations.&#160; The general
assessments, paid on a semi-annual basis, are computed upon the savings
institution&#146;s total assets, including consolidated subsidiaries, as reported in
the Bank&#146;s latest quarterly thrift financial report.&#160; The Bank was assessed approximately $191,000 for the fiscal year
ended December 31, 2004. </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF"><B><I>Transactions with
Related Parties</I></B><I>.</I>&#160; The Bank&#146;s authority to engage in
transactions with&#160; &#147;affiliates&#148; (<I>e.g</I>., any company that controls or is
under common control with an institution, including the Company and its
non-savings institution subsidiaries) is limited by federal law.&#160; The aggregate amount of covered transactions
with any individual affiliate is limited to 10% of the capital and surplus of
the savings institution.&#160; The aggregate
amount of covered transactions with all affiliates is limited to 20% of the
savings institution&#146;s capital and surplus.&#160;
Certain transactions with affiliates are required to be secured by
collateral in an amount and of a type described in federal law.&#160; The purchase of low quality assets from
affiliates is generally prohibited.&#160; The
transactions with affiliates must be on terms and under circumstances, that are
at least as favorable to the institution as those prevailing at the time for
comparable transactions with non-affiliated companies.&#160; In addition, savings institutions are
prohibited from lending to any affiliate that is engaged in activities that are
not permissible for bank holding companies and no savings institution may
purchase the securities of any affiliate other than a subsidiary. </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">The Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002 generally prohibits loans by the Company
to its executive officers and directors.&#160;
However, that Act contains a specific exception for loans by the Bank to
its executive officers and directors in compliance with federal banking
laws.&#160; The Bank&#146;s authority to extend
credit to executive officers, directors and 10% shareholders (&#147;insiders&#148;), as
well as entities such persons control, is also governed by federal law.&#160; Such loans are required to be made on terms
substantially the same as those offered to unaffiliated individuals and not
involve more than the normal risk of repayment.&#160; There is an exception for loans made pursuant to a benefit or
compensation program that is widely available to all employees of the
institution and does not give preference to insiders over other employees.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF"><B><I>Enforcement.</I></B>&#160; The OTS has primary enforcement
responsibility over savings institutions and has the authority to bring actions
against the institution and all institution-affiliated parties, including
stockholders, and any attorneys, appraisers and accountants who knowingly or
recklessly participate in wrongful action likely to have an adverse effect on
an insured institution.&#160; Formal
enforcement action may range from the issuance of a capital directive or cease
and desist order to removal of officers and/or directors to institution of
receivership, conservatorship or termination of deposit insurance.&#160; Civil penalties cover a wide range of
violations and can amount to $25,000 per day, or even $1 million per day in
especially egregious cases.&#160; The FDIC
has the authority to recommend to the Director of the OTS that enforcement
action to be taken with respect to a particular savings institution.&#160; If action is not taken by the Director, the
FDIC has authority to take such action under certain circumstances.&#160; Federal law also establishes criminal
penalties for certain violations. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF"><B><I>Standards for Safety
and Soundness</I></B><I>.</I>&#160; The federal banking agencies have adopted
Interagency Guidelines prescribing Standards for Safety and Soundness.&#160; The guidelines set forth the safety and
soundness standards that the federal banking agencies use to identify and
address problems at insured depository institutions before capital becomes
impaired.&#160; If the OTS determines that a
savings institution fails to meet any standard prescribed by the guidelines,
the OTS may require the institution to submit an acceptable plan to achieve
compliance with the standard. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">28</FONT></P>


<HR SIZE=5 NOSHADE>

<P STYLE="page-break-after:always"></P>



<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF"><B>Federal Home Loan Bank System </B></FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">The Bank is a member of the Federal Home Loan Bank (&#147;FHLB&#148;) System,
which consists of 12 regional FHLBs.&#160;
The FHLB provides a central credit facility primarily for member
institutions.&#160; In order to borrow from
the FHLB, the Bank is required to purchase shares of the FHLB&#146;s nonmarketable
equity securities at par. The Bank, as a member of the FHLB, is required to
acquire and hold shares of capital stock in that FHLB.&#160; The Bank was in compliance with this
requirement at December 31, 2004. For the year ended December 31, 2004, the
dividend yield on FHLB stock was 3.75%. </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">The FHLBs are required to provide funds for the resolution of insolvent
thrifts in the late 1980s and to contribute funds for affordable housing
programs.&#160; These requirements could
reduce the amount of dividends that the FHLBs pay to their members and could
also result in the FHLBs imposing a higher rate of interest on advances to
their members.&#160; If dividends were
reduced, or interest on future FHLB advances increased, the Bank&#146;s net interest
income would likely also be reduced.&#160;
Recent legislation has changed the structure of the FHLBs funding
obligations for insolvent thrifts, revised the capital structure of the FHLBs
and implemented entirely voluntary membership for FHLBs.&#160; Management cannot predict the effect that
these changes may have with respect to its FHLB membership. </FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF"><B>Federal Reserve System </B></FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">The Federal Reserve Board regulations require savings institutions to
maintain non-interest earning reserves against their transaction accounts
(primarily NOW and regular checking accounts).&#160;
For 2005, the regulations generally provide that reserves be maintained
against aggregate transaction accounts as follows: for accounts aggregating
$47.6 million or less (subject to adjustment by the Federal Reserve Board), the
reserve requirement is 3%; and for accounts aggregating greater than $47.6
million, the reserve requirement is 10% (subject to adjustment by the Federal
Reserve Board between 8% and 14%) against that portion of total transaction
accounts in excess of $47.6 million. The first $7.0 million of otherwise
reservable balances (subject to adjustments by the Federal Reserve Board) are
exempted from the reserve requirements.&#160;
At December 31, 2004, the Bank complied with the foregoing requirements.
</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF"><B>Community Reinvestment Act </B></FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">Under the Community Reinvestment Act (&#147;CRA&#148;), as implemented by OTS
regulations, a savings association has a continuing and affirmative obligation
consistent with its safe and sound operation to help meet the credit needs of
its entire community, including low and moderate income neighborhoods. The CRA
does not establish specific lending requirements or programs for financial
institutions nor does it limit an institution&#146;s discretion to develop the types
of products and services that it believes are best suited to its particular
community consistent with the CRA.&#160; The
CRA requires the OTS, in connection with its examination of an institution, to
assess the institution&#146;s record of meeting the credit needs of its community
and to take such record into account in its evaluation of applications by such
institution.&#160; The CRA requires public
disclosure of an institution&#146;s CRA rating.&#160;
The latest CRA rating of the Bank received from the OTS was
&#147;Satisfactory.&#148; </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">29</FONT></P>


<HR SIZE=5 NOSHADE>

<P STYLE="page-break-after:always"></P>



<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF"><B>F<A NAME=A018>ederal and State Taxatio</A>n </B></FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF"><B><I>General</I>.</B>&#160; The Company and the Bank report their income
on a consolidated basis using the accrual method of accounting, and are subject
to federal income taxation in the same manner as other corporations with some
exceptions, including particularly the Bank&#146;s reserve for bad debts discussed
below.&#160; The following discussion of tax
matters is intended only as a summary and does not purport to be a
comprehensive description of the tax rules applicable to the Bank or the
Company.&#160; The Bank was last audited by
the IRS for the year ended December 31, 1996.&#160;
For its 2004 taxable year, the Bank is subject to a maximum federal
income tax rate of 35%. </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF"><B><I>Bad Debt Reserves</I>.</B>&#160; For fiscal years beginning prior to December
31, 1995, thrift institutions which qualified under certain definitional tests
and other conditions of the Internal Revenue Code of 1986 (the &#147;Code&#148;) were
permitted to use certain favorable provisions to calculate their deductions
from taxable income for annual additions to their bad debt reserve.&#160; A reserve could be established for bad debts
on qualifying real property loans (generally secured by interests in real
property improved or to be improved) under (i) the Percentage of Taxable Income
Method (the &#147;PTI Method&#148;) or (ii)&#160; the
Experience Method.&#160; The reserve for
nonqualifying loans was computed using the Experience Method. </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">The Small Business Job Protection Act of 1996 (the &#147;1996 Act&#148;), which
was enacted on August 20, 1996, requires savings institutions to recapture (<I>i.e.</I>, take into income) certain portions
of their accumulated bad debt reserves. The 1996 Act repeals the reserve method
of accounting for bad debts effective for tax years beginning after 1995.&#160; Thrift institutions that would be treated as
small banks are allowed to utilize the Experience Method applicable to such
institutions, while thrift institutions that are treated as large banks (those
generally exceeding $500 million in assets) are required to use only the
specific charge-off method.&#160; Thus, the
PTI Method of accounting for bad debts is no longer available for any financial
institution.&#160;&#160; </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">A thrift institution required to change its method of computing
reserves for bad debts will treat such change as a change in method of
accounting, initiated by the taxpayer, and having been made with the consent of
the IRS.&#160; Any Section 481(a) adjustment
required to be taken into income with respect to such change&#160; generally will be taken into income ratably
over a six-taxable year period, beginning with the first taxable year beginning
after 1995, subject to the residential loan requirement.&#160; </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">Under the residential loan requirement provision, the recapture
required by the 1996 Act is suspended for each of two successive taxable years,
beginning with 1996, in which the Bank originates a minimum of certain residential
loans based upon the average of the principal amounts of such loans made by the
Bank during its six taxable years preceding its current taxable year. Under the
1996 Act, for its current and future taxable years, the Bank is permitted to
make additions to its tax bad debt reserves.&#160;
In addition, the Bank is required to recapture (<I>i.e., take into income</I>) over a six year
period the excess of the balance of its tax bad debt reserves as of December
31, 1995 over the balance of such reserves as of December 31, 1987. At December
31, 2004, the Bank had recaptured all of its bad debt reserves. </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF"><B><I>Distributions.</I></B>&#160; Under the 1996 Act, if the Bank makes
&#147;non-dividend distributions&#148; to the Company, such distributions will be
considered to have been made from the Bank&#146;s unrecaptured tax bad debt reserves
(including the balance of its reserves as of December 31, 1987) to the extent
thereof, and then from the Bank&#146;s supplemental reserve for losses on loans, to
the extent thereof, and an amount based on the amount distributed (but not in
excess of the amount of such reserves) will be included in the Bank&#146;s
income.&#160; Non-dividend distributions
include distributions in excess of the Bank&#146;s current and accumulated earnings
and profits, as calculated for federal income tax purposes, distributions in
redemption of stock, and distributions in partial or complete liquidation.&#160; Dividends paid out of the Bank&#146;s current or
accumulated earnings and profits will not be so included in the Bank&#146;s income. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">30</FONT></P>

<HR SIZE=5 NOSHADE>

<P STYLE="page-break-after:always"></P>

<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">The amount of additional taxable income triggered by a non-dividend is
an amount that, when reduced by the tax attributable to the income, is equal to
the amount of the distribution.&#160; Thus,
if the Bank makes a non-dividend  distribution to the Company, approximately one
and one-half times the amount of such distribution (but not in excess of the
amount of such reserves) would be includable in income for federal income tax
purposes, assuming a 35% federal corporate income tax rate.&#160; The Bank does not intend to pay dividends
that would result in a recapture of any portion of its bad debt reserves. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF"><B><I>Corporate
Alternative Minimum Tax.</I></B> The Code imposes a tax on
alternative minimum taxable income (&#147;AMTI&#148;) at a rate of 20%. For fiscal years
beginning prior to January 1, 1996, the excess of the bad debt reserve
deduction using the percentage of taxable income method over the deduction that
would have been allowable under the experience method is treated as a
preference item for purposes of computing the AMTI. Only 90% of AMTI can be
offset by net operating loss carryovers. The adjustment to AMTI based on book
income is an amount equal to 75% of the amount by which a corporation&#146;s
adjusted current earnings exceeds its AMTI (determined without regard to this
adjustment and prior to reduction for net operating losses). In addition, for
taxable years through 1995, an environmental tax of .12% of the excess of AMTI
(with certain modifications) over $2.0 million is imposed on corporations,
including the Bank, whether or not an Alternative Minimum Tax (&#147;AMT&#148;) is paid.
The Bank does not expect to be subject to the AMT. </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF"><B><I>Dividends Received
Deduction and Other Matters.</I></B> The Company may
exclude from its income 100% of dividends received from the Bank as a member of
the same affiliated group of corporations. The corporate dividends received
deduction is generally 70% in the case of dividends received from unaffiliated
corporations with which the Company and the Bank will not file a consolidated
tax return, except that if the Company and the Bank own more than 20% of the
stock of a corporation distributing a dividend, 80% of any dividends received
may be deducted. </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF"><B><I>Florida Taxation.</I></B>
The Bank files Florida franchise tax returns. For Florida franchise tax
purposes, savings institutions are presently taxed at a rate equal to 5.5% of
taxable income. For this purpose, &#147;taxable income&#148; generally means federal
taxable income, subject to certain adjustments (including the addition of
interest income on State and municipal obligations). The Bank is not currently
under audit with respect to its Florida franchise tax returns. </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">31</FONT></P>


<HR SIZE=5 NOSHADE>

<P STYLE="page-break-after:always"></P>


<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH="100%">
 <TR>
  <TD WIDTH="8%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF"><B>ITEM 2.</B></FONT></P></TD>

  <TD WIDTH=589 VALIGN=BOTTOM>
  <P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF"><B>C<A NAME=A029>ONTROLS AND PROCEDURE</A>S </B></FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>
</TABLE>
<BR>
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH="100%">
 <TR>
  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF"><B>Evaluation of disclosure controls and procedures </B></FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">The Company
  maintains controls and procedures designed to ensure that information
  required to be disclosed in the reports that the Company files or submits
  under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 is recorded, processed, summarized
  and reported within the time periods specified in the rules and forms of the
  Securities and Exchange Commission.&#160;
  Based upon their evaluation of those controls and procedures performed
  during the year, the chief executive and chief financial officers of the
  Company concluded that the Company&#146;s disclosure controls and procedures were
  effective as of December 31, 2004. </FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF"><B>Management Report On Internal Control Over Financial Reporting </B></FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">Our
  management is responsible for establishing and maintaining adequate internal
  control over financial reporting.&#160;
  Internal control is a process, effected by an entity&#146;s board of
  directors, management and other personnel, designed to provide reasonable
  assurance regarding the achievement of objectives in the following
  categories: effectiveness and efficiency of operations, reliability of
  financial reporting and compliance with applicable laws and regulations. </FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">All internal
  control systems, no matter how well designed, have inherent limitations.&#160; Therefore, even those systems determined
  to be effective can provide only reasonable assurance with respect to
  financial statement preparation and presentation. </FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">Under the
  supervision and with participation of our management, including our principal
  executive officer and principal financial officer, we are in the process of
  assessing the effectiveness of the company&#146;s internal control over financial
  reporting as of December 31, 2004. In making this assessment, we used the
  criteria set forth by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the
  Treadway Commission (COSO) in <I>Internal
  Control-Integrated Framework</I>. We expect to complete our assessment
  and report our conclusions on or before May 2, 2005. </FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">Hacker
  Johnson &amp; Smith PA, an independent registered public accounting firm,
  will issue an audit report on our assessment of the company&#146;s internal
  control over financial reporting.&#160;
  That report will be filed on or before May 2, 2005. </FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>
</TABLE>

  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">On January
  14, 2005, the Company entered into a definitive agreement for the Company and
  the Bank to be acquired by Colonial BancGroup, Inc., a bank holding company
  incorporated in Delaware with a subsidiary bank, Colonial Bank, N.A.,
  operating in Alabama, Florida, Georgia, Nevada and Texas. Under the terms of
  the agreement, shareholders of the Company will elect to receive either 2.0
  shares of Colonial stock or $42.00 in cash for each share of the Company
  stock they own. The cash consideration will be capped at 35% of the
  transaction and an over-election of cash will result in a pro rata
  distribution of stock. Completion of the transaction is subject to approval
  by the shareholders of the Company and various regulatory agencies.&#160; See Exhibit 99.1. </FONT></P></TD>

               year from your Retirement  date or, if sooner,  until the expiration of
               the term of the  Incentive  Stock Option.  All Incentive  Stock Options

     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2"><B>(a)</B> </FONT></TD>
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2"></FONT></TD>
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2"><B>Exercise of Incentive<BR>
Stock Option:</B> </FONT>
</TD>
     <TD> <P ALIGN="Justify"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2"><BR>
         Currently,  there are no regular  federal or state income or employment
                              tax  liabilities  upon the exercise of an  Incentive  Stock Option (see
                              Incentive Stock Option Holding  Period),  although the excess,  if any,
                              of the Fair Market  Value of the shares of Common  Stock on the date of
                              exercise   over  the  Option  Price  will  be  treated  as  income  for
                              alternative  minimum  tax ("AMT")  purposes  and may subject you to AMT
                              in the year of exercise.  Please check with your tax advisor.
</FONT></P> </TD></TR>
<TR VALIGN="TOP">
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR VALIGN="TOP">
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2"></FONT></TD>
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2"><B>(b)</B> </FONT></TD>
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2"></FONT></TD>
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2"><B>Disqualifying Disposition:</B> </FONT>
</TD>
     <TD> <P ALIGN="Justify"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">In the event of a  disqualifying  disposition  (described  below),  you
may be required to pay FFLC Bancorp,  Inc. or its Affiliates  (based on
the federal  and state  regulations  in place at the time of  exercise)
an  amount  sufficient  to  satisfy  all  federal,  state and local tax
withholding.
</FONT></P> </TD></TR>
<TR VALIGN="TOP">
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR VALIGN="TOP">
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2"></FONT></TD>
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2"><B>(c)</B> </FONT></TD>
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2"></FONT></TD>
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2"><B>Incentive Stock Option<BR>
Holding Period:</B> </FONT>
</TD>
     <TD> <P ALIGN="Justify"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">In order to receive Incentive Stock Option tax treatment under
Section 422 of the Code, you may not dispose of shares acquired under
an Incentive Stock Option Award (i) for two (2) years from the Date
of Grant and (ii) for one (1) year after the date you exercise your
Incentive Stock Option. <B>You must notify the Company within ten (10)
days of an early disposition of Common Stock (i.e., a "disqualifying
disposition").</B> </FONT>
</P> </TD></TR>
<TR VALIGN="TOP">
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR VALIGN="TOP">
     <TD COLSPAN="4"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2"><B>Designation of Beneficiary:</B> </FONT>
</TD>
     <TD> <P ALIGN="Justify"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">You  may  designate  a  beneficiary,   on  a  form  acceptable  to  the
                           Committee,  to receive rights under this Incentive  Stock Option Award,
                           in the event of your death.  If a  beneficiary  is not  designated  the
                           Award will become part of your estate.
</FONT></P> </TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<BR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><FONT FACE="Times New Roman" size=2>3</FONT></P><HR SIZE=5 COLOR=GRAY STYLE="page-break-after:always">

     <TH></TH>
     <TH></TH></TR>
<TR VALIGN="TOP">
     <TD WIDTH="30%"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2"><B>Non-Transferability:</B> </FONT>
</TD>
     <TD WIDTH="70%"> <P ALIGN="Justify"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">This Incentive Stock Option Award shall not be  transferred,  assigned,
                    hypothecated,  or  disposed  of in any manner by you other than by will
                    or the laws of intestate succession.
</FONT></P> </TD></TR>
<TR VALIGN="TOP">
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR VALIGN="TOP">
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2"><B>Plan Governs:</B> </FONT>
</TD>
     <TD> <P ALIGN="Justify"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">Notwithstanding  anything in this  Incentive  Stock Option Award  Agreement to the contrary,  the
                                        terms of this Incentive  Stock Option Award  Agreement shall be subject
                                        to the  terms  and  conditions  of the  Plan,  a copy of  which  may be
                                        obtained  from  the  Company.   This   Incentive   Stock  Option  Award
                                        Agreement  is subject  to all  interpretations,  amendments,  rules and
                                        regulations  promulgated  by the  Committee  from time to time pursuant
                                        to the Plan.  Any  capitalized  terms shall have the  meaning  given to
                                        such terms in the Plan.
</FONT></P> </TD></TR>
<TR VALIGN="TOP">
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR>

     <TD> <P ALIGN="Justify"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">Neither  the Plan nor this  Award  Agreement  create  any  right on the
part of any  individual to continue in the  employment of FFLC Bancorp,
Inc. or any Affiliate of FFLC Bancorp, Inc.
</FONT></P> </TD></TR>
<TR VALIGN="TOP">
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
     <TD><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR>

</TD>
     <TD> <P ALIGN="Justify"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2">The  Committee  may amend or modify this  Incentive  Stock Option Award
                        from time to time, prospectively or retroactively;  provided,  however,
                        that no such  amendment  or  modification  will  adversely  affect  the
                        rights of the  Participant  under this Award  Agreement  without his or
                        her written consent.
</FONT></P> </TD></TR>

<P ALIGN=right><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif" SIZE="2"><B>Exhibit 13</B> </FONT> </P>

<P align=center><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2><B>FFLC BANCORP, INC.<BR>2004 ANNUAL REPORT</B></FONT></P>

<P align=center><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2><B>OUR MISSION</B></FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>Our mission is to operate First Federal Savings Bank as a community bank, in a manner consistent with the high expectations of our stockholders, customers and employees. We will achieve attractive financial results for our stockholders, provide quality financial services and products to our customers, and offer rewarding careers to our employees, while maintaining a high level of personal service and integrity.&nbsp; The Company&#146;s primary goals are to: provide an attractive return to its stockholders, as measured by long-term capital appreciation and the continued payment of reasonable dividends; provide a competitive, progressive and profitable array of financial services and products in a manner focused on excellent customer service; attract and retain highly-motivated, top-quality employees; and make a positive impact on the communities that we serve. </FONT></P>

<P align=center><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2><B>FORWARD-LOOKING STATEMENTS</B></FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>The Private Securities Litigation Reform Act of 1995 evidences Congress&#146; determination that the disclosure of forward-looking information is desirable for investors and encourages such disclosure by providing a safe harbor for forward-looking statements by corporate management.&nbsp; This Annual Report, including the Letter to Stockholders and the Management&#146;s Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations, contains forward-looking statements that involve risk and uncertainty.&nbsp; In order to comply with the terms of the safe harbor, the Company notes that a variety of factors could cause the Company&#146;s actual results and experience to differ materially from the anticipated results or other expectations expressed in the Company&#146;s forward-looking statements.&nbsp; The risks and uncertainties that may affect the operations, performance, development, growth projections and results of the
Company&#146;s business include, but are not limited to, the growth of the economy, interest rate movements, timely development by the Company of technology enhancements for its products and operating systems, the impact of competitive products, services and pricing, customer business requirements, Congressional legislation and similar matters.&nbsp; Readers of this report are cautioned not to place undue reliance on forward-looking statements which are subject to influence by the named risk factors and unanticipated future events.&nbsp; Actual results, accordingly, may differ materially from management expectations. </FONT></P>

<P align=center><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>Inside Cover</FONT></P>

<P><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2><B><A name=A039>CORPORATE PROFIL</A>E&nbsp; </B></FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>FFLC Bancorp, Inc. (&#147;FFLC&#148; or the &#147;Holding Company&#148;) was incorporated in Delaware on September 16, 1993, and acquired First Federal Savings Bank of Lake County (the &#147;Bank&#148;) (together, the &#147;Company&#148;) in connection with the Bank&#146;s conversion to stock form on January 4, 1994.&nbsp; The Holding Company which transacts its business through its subsidiary, the Bank is a savings and loan holding company subject to regulation by the Office of Thrift Supervision (&#147;OTS&#148;). The Bank is a community-oriented savings institution, chartered in 1934, which offers a variety of financial services to individuals and businesses primarily located in Lake, Sumter, Citrus and Marion Counties in Florida.&nbsp; The deposits of the Bank are insured by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (&#147;FDIC&#148;) through the Savings Association Insurance Fund (&#147;SAIF&#148;).&nbsp; </FONT></P>

<P align=center><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>3</FONT></P>

<HR noShade SIZE=5>

<P style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always"></P>




<P align=center><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2><B>
<A name=A042><IMG src="firstfederal.jpg"></A></B></FONT></P>


<P><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>Dear Stockholders: </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>I am very pleased to be able to report to you that 2004 was not only another successful and profitable year, but also a year of significant milestones.&nbsp; During 2004, the Company celebrated its tenth anniversary of being a public company, its 70th anniversary as a financial institution, and surpassed $1 billion in total assets.&nbsp; The Board of Directors and the rest of the management team join me in expressing our sincere appreciation for your support, the hard work of our employees and the wonderful reception we have received from our customers and the communities we serve. </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>During 2004, the Company earned $10.0 million compared with $9.1 million for 2003, an increase of 10%.&nbsp; On a per share basis, the Company reported basic net income per share of $1.86 for 2004, compared to $1.70 for 2003, and diluted net income per share of $1.83 for 2004 and $1.67 for 2003.&nbsp; The increase in net income for 2004 compared to 2003 was primarily the result of an increase in net interest income of $3.8 million.&nbsp; That increase occurred in large part because of the continued reduction in the Bank&#146;s cost of funds as a result of favorable market interest rates. </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>I am pleased to report that others also recognized our profitable performance and growth, and our stock price rose approximately 22% during the year, from $28.75 to $35.10.&nbsp; In addition, cash dividends paid per share increased from $.46 to $.52, an increase of 13%, from 2003 to 2004.&nbsp; Since our public offering in 1994, your stock has yielded an average annual return, including dividends, of 25.1%. </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>We have been very fortunate to serve a growing market, and that growth is reflected in the asset growth of FFLC.&nbsp; During 2004, total assets grew 12%, from $947.9 million at December 31, 2003 to $1.07 billion at December 31, 2004.&nbsp; During 2004, loans receivable increased by $116 million (or, 15%) that was primarily funded by an increase in deposits of $90 million (or, 13%) and in FHLB advances of $20 million (or, 15%).&nbsp;&nbsp; I am also pleased to report that FFLC&#146;s stockholder&#146;s equity increased from $77 million to $84 million during 2004, and book value per share increased from $14.33 at December 31, 2003 to $15.62 at December 31, 2004.&nbsp;&nbsp; In order to continue serving the growing needs of our customer base, we opened our 16<SUP>th</SUP> branch office in May 2004, on SR 466 in the Villages area. </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>In what&nbsp;will be the next exciting chapter in our corporate history, we recently announced that FFLC had signed a definitive agreement to merge with Colonial BankGroup, Inc. (&#147;Colonial&#148;).&nbsp; We believe this merger provides substantial benefit to our stockholders.&nbsp; In addition, linking with Colonial will provide our customers with additional products and an expanded network of branch offices for more convenient banking. </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>From a financial perspective, FFLC stockholders will have several options.&nbsp; Our stockholders can elect to receive two shares of Colonial stock for each share of FFLC, to receive $42 cash per share for each share of FFLC, or to receive a combination of Colonial stock and cash.&nbsp; In the aggregate, no more than 35% of the exchange can be in cash.&nbsp; An over-election of cash will result in a pro rata distribution of stock. </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>We are excited to be affiliating with Colonial, which is headquartered in Montgomery, Alabama, and also has a presence in Georgia, Texas and Nevada.&nbsp; However, Florida has been Colonial&#146;s focus for the past decade, and business in Florida now represents over 50% of Colonial&#146;s assets.&nbsp; Over the past ten years, Colonial will have gone from no presence in Florida to being the fifth largest commercial bank in the state following our merger. </FONT></P>

<P align=center><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>4</FONT></P>

<HR noShade SIZE=5>

<P style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always"></P>




<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>While significantly larger than FFLC, Colonial shares in the same approach to community banking, and the same focus on providing great customer service.&nbsp; The members of the FFLC Board of Directors will remain involved after the merger, and will continue to have local lending authority.&nbsp; In addition, our customer service team of lenders and branch personnel will remain substantially unchanged.&nbsp; As a result, we will continue to offer the quality customer service for which First Federal Savings Bank has been known. </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>We sincerely appreciate the support we have received from our stockholders over the past eleven years as a public company.&nbsp; We look forward to the future with our new partner, Colonial BankGroup, Inc., and to the opportunity to continue providing quality banking services throughout Central Florida. </FONT></P>


<P><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>Cordially yours, </FONT></P>


<P><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>Stephen T. Kurtz<BR>President &amp; CEO</FONT></P>

<P align=center><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>5</FONT></P>

<HR noShade SIZE=5>

<P style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always"></P>




<A name=A043>&nbsp;</A>
<P align=center><IMG src="logo1new.jpg"></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>Visit First Federal&#146;s website at http://www.1stfederal.com.&nbsp; This site serves as a portal for First Federal banking services, local news, and information regarding our communities.&nbsp; From this site, customers can gain access to First Federal Online Banking, our fully interactive banking system, that allows bill payments, account inquiries, transfer of funds and more. In addition, commercial customers can access cash management tools, make tax payments and make payroll direct deposit payments through First Federal Online Banking.&nbsp; You&#146;ll also find current information about the Bank&#146;s locations, products and services at our website. </FONT></P>


<P><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>Investors can also get the&nbsp; latest information regarding FFLC, including stock quotes, press releases, SEC filings, beneficial ownership reports, and other supplemental data, in the &#147;FFLC Bancorp&#148; section of our website.&nbsp;&nbsp; </FONT></P>

<P align=center><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2><I>www.1stfederal.com <BR></I>First Federal online logo</FONT></P>

<P align=center><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>6</FONT></P>

<HR noShade SIZE=5>

<P style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always"></P>




<P align=center><IMG src="logo2new.jpg"></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>First Federal introduced First Federal Online Banking in July 2000 through the Bank&#146;s website at http://www.1stfederal.com. First Federal customers can now access practically their entire First Federal relationship through the website, 24 hours a day, 7 days a week.&nbsp; From the First Federal website, customers can view our online banking product and may enroll online.&nbsp; After receiving their user ID and password, customers may log-on to check balances, pay their bills online, reconcile their account statements, transfer funds from one account to another, review account histories, reorder checks and more. First Federal Online Banking is just one more added convenience to banking with First Federal. </FONT></P>

<P align=center><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2><B><IMG src="firstfederal.jpg"></B></FONT></P>

<P align=center><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>9</FONT></P>

<HR noShade SIZE=5>

<P style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always"></P>




<P align=center><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2><B>M
<A name=A045>ANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS OF FINANCIAL CONDITIO</A>N&nbsp; <BR>AND RESULTS OF OPERATIONS</B></FONT></P>


<P><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2><B>GENERAL&nbsp; </B></FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>First Federal Savings Bank of Lake County, the subsidiary of FFLC, was organized in 1934 as a federally chartered savings and loan association and converted to a federally chartered stock savings bank on January 4, 1994. The Bank&#146;s principal business continues to be attracting retail deposits from the general public and investing those deposits, together with principal repayments on loans and investments and funds generated from operations, primarily in mortgage loans secured by one-to-four-family, owner-occupied homes, commercial loans, consumer loans and, to a lesser extent, construction loans and other loans, and multi-family residential mortgage loans. In addition, the Bank holds investments permitted by federal laws and regulations including securities issued by the U.S. Government and agencies thereof. The Bank&#146;s revenues are derived principally from interest on its loan and mortgage-backed securities portfolios and
interest and dividends on its investment securities.&nbsp; </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>The Bank is a community-oriented savings institution offering a variety of financial services to meet the needs of the communities it serves. The Bank&#146;s deposit gathering and lending markets are primarily concentrated in the communities surrounding its full service offices located in Lake, Sumter, Citrus and Marion counties in central Florida. Management believes that its offices are located in communities that generally can be characterized as rural service and retirement communities with residential neighborhoods comprised predominately of one-to-four-family residences. The Bank is the largest (by asset size) locally-based financial institution in Lake County, and serves its market area with a wide selection of residential mortgage loans and other retail financial services. Management considers the Bank&#146;s reputation for financial strength and customer service as a major advantage in attracting and retaining customers in its
market area and believes it benefits from its community orientation as well as its established deposit base and level of core deposits. </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>On January 14, 2005, FFLC Bancorp, Inc. (the &#147;Holding Company&#148;) entered into a definitive agreement for the Holding Company and First Federal Savings Bank of Lake County (the &#147;Bank&#148;) to be acquired by Colonial BancGroup, Inc., a bank holding company incorporated in Delaware with a subsidiary bank, Colonial Bank, N.A., operating in Alabama, Florida, Georgia, Nevada, Tennessee, and Texas.&nbsp;&nbsp; Under the terms of the agreement, stockholders of the Holding Company will elect to receive either 2.0 shares of Colonial stock or $42.00 in cash for each share of the Holding Company stock they own. The cash consideration will be capped at 35% of the transaction and an over-election of cash will result in a pro rata distribution of stock.&nbsp;&nbsp; Completion of the transaction is subject to approval by the stockholders of the Holding Company and various regulatory agencies.&nbsp;&nbsp; </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>The Company&#146;s net income from operations increased 9.5% to $10.0 million for the year ended December 31, 2004 from $9.1 million for the year 2003.&nbsp; The Company&#146;s total assets increased 12.4% to $1,065.3 million at December 31, 2004 from $947.9 million at December 31, 2003.&nbsp; That increase resulted primarily from a 15.1% increase in net loans to $884.0 million at December 31, 2004 from $768.0 million at December 31, 2003, reflecting increased local loan demand.&nbsp; Securities decreased 9.3% or $7.6 million during 2004.&nbsp; Deposits increased 12.7% to $795.2 million at December 31, 2004 from $705.6 million at December 31, 2003.&nbsp; Advances from the Federal Home Loan Bank increased $20.0 million, to $153.0 million at December 31, 2004 from $133.0 million at December 31, 2003. </FONT></P>


<P><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2><B>CRITICAL ACCOUNTING POLICIES </B></FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>Our financial condition and results of operations are sensitive to accounting measurements and estimates of matters that are inherently uncertain.&nbsp; When applying accounting policies in areas that are subjective in nature, we use our best judgment to arrive at the carrying value of certain assets.&nbsp; The most critical accounting policy we apply is related to the valuation of the loan portfolio. </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>A variety of factors impact the carrying value of the loan portfolio, including the calculation of the allowance for loan losses, the valuation of underlying collateral, the timing of loan charge-offs and the amount and amortization of loan fees and deferred origination costs. </FONT></P>

<P align=center><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>10</FONT></P>

<HR noShade SIZE=5>

<P style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always"></P>




<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>We believe that the determination of the allowance for loan losses represents a critical accounting policy.&nbsp; The allowance for loan losses is maintained at a level management considers to be adequate to absorb probable loan losses inherent in the portfolio, based on evaluations of the collectibility and historical loss experience of loans.&nbsp; Credit losses are charged and recoveries are credited to the allowance.&nbsp; In estimating probable credit losses, provisions for loan losses are based on our review of our historical loan loss experience and such other factors which, in management&#146;s judgment, deserve consideration under existing economic conditions. The allowance is based on ongoing assessments of the probable estimated losses inherent in the loan portfolio.&nbsp; Our methodology for assessing the appropriate allowance level consists of several key elements described below. </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>Larger commercial loans that exhibit probable or observed credit weaknesses are subject to individual review.&nbsp; Where appropriate, reserves are allocated to individual loans based on our estimate of the borrower&#146;s ability to repay the loan given the availability of collateral, other sources of cash flows, and available legal options.&nbsp; Included in the review of individual loans are those that are impaired as provided in Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No. 114, &#147;<I>Accounting by Creditors for Impairment of a Loan</I>&#148; as amended.&nbsp; Any specific reserves for impaired loans are measured based on the fair market value of the underlying collateral.&nbsp; We evaluate the collectibility of both principal and interest when assessing the need for a special reserve.&nbsp; Historical loss rates are applied to other commercial loans not subject to specific reserve allocations. </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>Homogenous loans, such as installment and residential mortgage loans, are not individually reviewed by management.&nbsp; Reserves are established for each pool of such loans based on the expected net charge-offs.&nbsp; Loss rates are based on the average net charge-off history by loan category. </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>Historical loss rates for commercial and consumer loans may be adjusted for significant factors that, in management&#146;s judgment, reflect the impact of current conditions on loss recognition.&nbsp; Factors which management considers in the analysis include the effects of the local economy, trends in the nature and volume of loans (delinquencies, charge-offs, nonaccrual and problem loans), changes in the internal lending policies and credit standards, collection practices, and examination results from bank regulatory agencies and our internal credit review function.&nbsp; An unallocated reserve is maintained to recognize the imprecision in estimating and measuring loss when evaluating reserves for individual loans or pools of loans.&nbsp; Specific reserves on individual loans and historical loss rates are reviewed throughout the year and adjusted as necessary based on changing borrower and collateral conditions and actual collection
and charge-off experience. </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>Based on the procedures discussed above, management believes that allowance for loan losses was adequate to absorb estimated loan losses associated with the loan portfolio at December 31, 2004.&nbsp; Actual results could differ from these estimates.&nbsp; However, since the allowance is affected by management&#146;s judgment and uncertainties, there is the likelihood that materially different amounts would be reported under different conditions or assumptions.&nbsp; To the extent that the economy, collateral values, reserve factors, or the nature and volume of problem loans change, we may need to adjust the provision for loan losses.&nbsp; Material additions to our provision for loan losses would result in a decrease in net income and capital. </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>The allowance for loan losses is also discussed as part of &#147;Results of Operations&#148; and in Note 3 to the consolidated financial statements.&nbsp; The significant accounting policies are discussed in Note 1 to the consolidated financial statements. </FONT></P>

<P align=center><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>11</FONT></P>

<HR noShade SIZE=5>

<P style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always"></P>





<P><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2><B>REGULATION AND LEGISLATION&nbsp; </B></FONT></P>


<P><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2><I>General&nbsp; </I></FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>The operating results of the Bank are affected by Federal laws and regulations and the Bank is subject to extensive regulation, examination and supervision by the OTS as its chartering agency, and the FDIC as the deposit insurer. The Bank is a member of the Federal Home Loan Bank (&#147;FHLB&#148;) System and its deposit accounts are insured up to applicable limits by the FDIC under the SAIF. The Bank must file reports with the OTS and the FDIC concerning its activities and financial condition in addition to obtaining regulatory approvals prior to entering into certain transactions such as mergers with, or acquisitions of, other financial institutions. The OTS and the FDIC conduct periodic examinations to test the Bank&#146;s compliance with various regulatory requirements. The activities of the Company and the Bank are governed by the Home Owner&#146;s Loan Act, as amended (the &#147;HOLA&#148;), and, in certain respects, the Federal
Deposit Insurance Act (the &#147;FDIA&#148;).&nbsp; A more complete description of the HOLA and FDIA is included in the Form 10-K.&nbsp; </FONT></P>


<P><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2><I>Capital Requirements&nbsp; </I></FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>The capital regulations of the OTS require savings institutions to meet three capital standards: a 1.5% tangible capital standard; a 3% leverage (core capital) ratio; and an 8% risk-based capital standard. Under the OTS final rule implementing the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation Improvement Act&nbsp; (&#147;FDICIA&#148;), a well-capitalized institution is defined generally as one that meets the following capital standards: a 5% tangible capital standard; a 6% leverage (core capital) ratio; and a 10% risk-based capital standard, and has not been notified by the OTS that it is in a &#147;troubled condition.&#148; At December 31, 2004, the Bank met each of its capital requirements and met the criteria of a &#147;well-capitalized&#148; institution as defined above. </FONT></P>


<P><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2><I>Insurance of Deposit Accounts&nbsp; </I></FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>The FDIC has adopted a risk-based deposit insurance system that assesses deposit insurance premiums according to the level of risk involved in an institution&#146;s activities. An institution&#146;s risk category is based upon whether the institution is classified as &#147;well capitalized,&#148; &#147;adequately capitalized&#148; or &#147;less than adequately capitalized&#148; and one of three supervisory subcategories within each capital group.&nbsp; The supervisory subgroup to which an institution is assigned is based on a supervisory evaluation and information which the FDIC determines to be relevant to the institution&#146;s financial condition and the risk posed to the deposit insurance fund.&nbsp; The FDIC has authority to raise premiums if deemed necessary.&nbsp; If such action is taken, it could have an adverse effect on the earnings of the institution. </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>Under the FDIA, insurance of deposits may be terminated by the FDIC upon a finding that the institution has engaged in unsafe or unsound practices, is in an unsafe or unsound condition to continue operations or has violated any applicable law, regulation, rule, order or condition imposed by the FDIC or the OTS.&nbsp; The management of the Bank does not know of any practice, condition or violation that might lead to termination of deposit insurance.&nbsp; </FONT></P>


<P><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2><B>CREDIT RISK&nbsp; </B></FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>The Bank&#146;s primary business is lending on residential real estate, commercial real estate and consumer financing, activities with the inherent risk of generating potential loan losses the magnitude of which depend on a variety of factors affecting borrowers which are beyond the control of the Bank. The Bank has underwriting guidelines and credit review procedures designed to minimize such credit losses. </FONT></P>

<P align=center><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>12</FONT></P>

<HR noShade SIZE=5>

<P style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always"></P>





<P><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2><B>RESULTS OF OPERATIONS&nbsp; </B></FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>The Company&#146;s results of operations are dependent primarily on net interest income, which is the difference between the income earned on its interest-earning assets, primarily its loans, mortgage-backed securities and investment securities, and its interest-bearing liabilities, consisting of deposits and borrowings. The operating expenses of the Company principally consist of employee compensation, occupancy expenses and other general and administrative expenses. The Company&#146;s results of operations are also significantly affected by general economic and competitive conditions, particularly changes in market interest rates, government policies and actions of regulatory authorities.&nbsp; </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>Net interest income represents the difference between income on interest-earning assets and expense on interest-bearing liabilities. Net interest income depends upon the volume of interest-earning assets and interest-bearing liabilities and the interest rates earned or paid on them.&nbsp; </FONT></P>

<P align=center><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>13</FONT></P>

<HR noShade SIZE=5>

<P style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always"></P>




<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>The following table sets forth, for the periods indicated, information regarding (i) the total dollar amount of interest and dividend income of the Company from interest-earning assets and the resultant average yields; (ii) the total dollar amount of interest expense on interest-bearing liabilities and the resultant average costs; (iii) net interest/dividend income; (iv) interest-rate spread; (v) net interest margin; and (vi) weighted average yields and rates at December 31, 2004.&nbsp; Yields and costs were derived by dividing income or expense by the average balance of assets or liabilities, respectively, for the periods shown.&nbsp; The average balance of loans includes loans on which the Company has discontinued accruing interest. The yields and costs include fees which are considered to constitute adjustments to yields. </FONT></P>

Information is provided in each category with respect to (i) changes attributable to changes in volume (changes in volume multiplied by prior rate), (ii) changes attributable to changes in rate (changes in rate multiplied by prior volume) and (iii) changes attributable to changes in rate/volume (changes in rate multiplied by changes in volume). </FONT></P>

<P align=center><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>15</FONT></P>

<HR noShade SIZE=5>

<P style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always"></P>





<P><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2><B>CAPITAL RESOURCES&nbsp; </B></FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>The Bank&#146;s sources of funds include proceeds from payments and prepayments on mortgage loans and mortgage-backed securities, proceeds from the maturities of investment securities and deposits.&nbsp; While maturities and scheduled amortization of loans and investment securities are predictable sources of funds, deposit inflows and mortgage prepayments are greatly influenced by local conditions, general interest rates, and regulatory changes.&nbsp; </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>At December 31, 2004, the Bank had outstanding commitments to originate $18.3 million of loans, to fund unused lines of credit of $70.0 million, to fund the undisbursed portion of loans in process of $47.5 million and to fund $3.1 million in outstanding standby letters of credit.&nbsp; The Bank believes that it will have sufficient funds available to meet its commitments.&nbsp; At December 31, 2004, certificates of deposit which were scheduled to mature in one year or less totaled $253.9 million. Management believes, based on past experience, that a significant portion of those funds will remain with the Bank.&nbsp; </FONT></P>


<P><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2><B>REGULATORY CAPITAL REQUIREMENTS&nbsp; </B></FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>As a federally-chartered financial institution, the Bank is required to maintain certain minimum amounts of regulatory capital. Regulatory capital is not a valuation allowance and has not been created by charges against earnings. The following table provides a summary of the capital requirements, the Bank&#146;s regulatory capital and the amounts in excess of the requirements at December 31, 2004:&nbsp; </FONT></P>

<P><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2><B>QUANTITATIVE AND QUALITATIVE DISCLOSURES ABOUT MARKET RISK </B></FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>Market risk is the risk of loss from adverse changes in market prices and rates.&nbsp; The Company&#146;s market risk arises primarily from interest-rate risk inherent in its lending and deposit taking activities. The Company has little or no risk related to trading accounts, commodities or foreign exchange. </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>Management actively monitors and manages its interest rate risk exposure.&nbsp; The primary objective in managing interest-rate risk is to limit, within established guidelines, the adverse impact of changes in interest rates on the Company&#146;s net interest income and capital, while adjusting the Company&#146;s asset-liability structure to obtain the maximum yield-cost spread on that structure.&nbsp; Management relies primarily on its asset-liability structure to control interest rate risk. However, a sudden and substantial increase in interest rates could adversely impact the Company&#146;s earnings, to the extent that the interest rates borne by assets and liabilities do not change at the same speed, to the same extent, or on the same basis. </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>Disclosure about the fair value of financial instruments, which reflect changes in market prices and rates, can be found in Note 9 of the notes to the consolidated financial statements. </FONT></P>

<P align=center><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>16</FONT></P>

<HR noShade SIZE=5>

<P style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always"></P>





<P><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2><B>OFF-BALANCE SHEET ARRANGEMENTS AND AGGREGATE CONTRACTUAL OBLIGATIONS </B></FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>The Company is a party to financial instruments with off-balance-sheet risk in the normal course of business to meet the financing needs of its customers and to reduce its own exposure to fluctuations in interest rates. These financial instruments include commitments to extend credit, unused lines of credit, undisbursed loans in process and standby letters of credit. These instruments involve, to varying degrees, elements of credit and interest-rate risk in excess of the amounts recognized in the consolidated balance sheet.&nbsp; The contract amounts of these instruments reflect the extent of the Company&#146;s involvement in these financial instruments. </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>The Company&#146;s exposure to credit loss in the event of nonperformance by the other party to the financial instrument for commitments to extend credit, unused lines of credit, undisbursed loans in process and standby letters of credit is represented by the contractual amount of those instruments.&nbsp; The Company uses the same credit policies in making commitments as it does for on-balance sheet instruments. </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>Commitments to extend credit are agreements to lend to a customer as long as there is no violation of any condition established in the contract.&nbsp; Commitments generally have fixed-expiration dates or other termination clauses and may require payment of a fee.&nbsp; Since certain commitments expire without being drawn upon, the total committed amounts do not necessarily represent future cash requirements.&nbsp; The Company evaluates each customer&#146;s credit worthiness on a case-by-case basis.&nbsp; The amount of collateral obtained, if it is deemed necessary by the Company upon extension of credit, is based on management&#146;s credit evaluation of the counter party. </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>Standby letters of credit are conditional commitments issued by the Company to guarantee the performance of a customer to a third party.&nbsp; The credit risk involved in issuing letters of credit is essentially the same as that involved in extending loans to customers. </FONT></P>

<P align=justify><FONT face="TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF" size=2>The following is a summary of the Company&#146;s contractual obligations, including certain on-balance sheet obligations, at December 31, 2004 (in thousands): </FONT></P>
